article.description: Ticha Penicheiro scored nine of her 18 points in the fourth quarter to rally the Sacramento Monarchs to a 70-63 victory over the New York Liberty on Sunday.
article.headline: Penicheiro scores nine in fourth as Monarchs shake up Liberty
article.linkText: Penicheiro leads Monarchs' late rally past Liberty
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Ticha Penicheiro and Kara Lawson rallied the Sacramento Monarchs to their first road victory of the season.

Penicheiro scored 16 of her 18 points in the second half -- including nine in the fourth quarter -- and Lawson had six of her 11 in the final period to lift the Monarchs to a 70-63 victory over the New York Liberty on Sunday at Madison Square Garden.

Penicheiro and Lawson totaled 15 years of experience in the starting backcourt for Sacramento while going against Liberty rookies Leilani Mitchell and Essence Carson.

"Maybe it is the experience versus a younger team," Penicheiro said. "We just had a conscious effort today of really trying to get this win. We hadn't won on the road. We thought that in the past games we really have folded in the fourth quarter, so today we talked about being focused throughout the whole game. And I thought we did that."

Nicole Powell had 13 points, Adrian Williams-Strong added 11 points and nine rebounds, and Rebekkah Brunson 10 points as all the starters scored in double digits for Sacramento (3-4), which had lost its first three on the road.

"I thought we played great," Penicheiro said. "We had a lot of people contributing for this win. It's a great win for us."

Lisa Willis scored 11 points, Cathrine Kraayeveld had 10, and Tiffany Jackson added 10 points and nine rebounds for the Liberty (3-4), who had won two straight overall and three in a row at home. New York, tops in the league in 3-point shooting, was just 6-for-21 from beyond the arc.

Shameka Christon, the Liberty's leading scorer at 16.2 points per game coming in, finished with seven on 2-for-12 shooting from the field.

"They came ready to play today and I'm not sure if we did," Christon said. "I have to be better for my teammates. ... We got shots and we just didn't knock them down."

Mitchell, making her second straight start in place of the injured Loree Moore, finished with just two points on 0-for-4 shooting from the field but had a team season-high eight assists. Mitchell had 18 points on 6-for-6 shooting and added seven assists in the win over Houston on Friday night.

"They got up and pressured us, and I think it kind of got to me a little," Mitchell said. "I just didn't take very good care of the ball. We did get some open looks, they just weren't falling for us."

After Willis' 3-pointer gave New York a 56-50 lead with 8:10 left in the fourth quarter, the Monarchs went on a 15-1 run to take an eight point lead. Lawson's three-point play with 3:43 to go capped a 10-point spurt and gave Sacramento a four-point lead, and her 3-pointer 1:19 later pushed the advantage to 65-57.

Kraayeveld hit a jumper with 2:12 left -- New York's second field goal of the quarter -- and Christon had a fast-break layup 23 seconds later to pull the Liberty to 65-61. However, Christon missed a 16-foot jumper along the left baseline with 1:09 to go, and Penicheiro hit a jumper and two free throws in the final minute to seal the win.

"We have not closed out games well so far this year," Sacramento coach Jenny Boucek said. "We've been in position to win several of the games we lost. We haven't closed out the games and executed down the stretch. This is as much about us learning how to do that with this group we've got here this year as anything."

The Monarchs jumped out to a 9-1 lead in the first 3:13 of the game.

New York rebounded by scoring the next 13 points, including six by Carson. Willis hit a 3 and Jackson had a layup to stretch the Liberty's lead to 19-11 in the final minute of the first quarter.

Sacramento had an 8-1 run, capped by two layups by Brunson, to take a 22-21 lead with 4 1/2 left in the second quarter.

However, Erin Thorn and Mitchell hit two free throws each, and then Thorn hit a 3 to give the Liberty a 28-22 lead a minute later.

New York shot just 2-for-11 from the field in the second quarter, but still scored 17 points thanks to a 12-for-14 effort on free throws.
